AGI - Despite international appeals because Israel and Hamas discuss the proposal of a truce announced two days ago by American President Joe Biden, Israel's attacks on the Gaza Strip and in particular to Rafah continue. While the war is about to take 8 months, despite the protests of the international community, the Israeli army continues the offensive on the southern city bordering Egypt. From what has now become the epicenter of the war, about a million Palestinians have fled in front of the advance, under aerial cover of the Israeli forces. "Due to Israeli operations, thousands of families were forced to flee. The 36 refuges in Rafah of the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-25/ meeting-tajani-mustafa-resumption-funding-unrwa-26520836/">UNRWA </a> are now empty", according to the UN agency. Local witnesses report seeing Israeli military vehicles in Western and Central Rafah and hearing strong explosions, accompanied by fighting, continuous shootings with Apache drones and helicopters. The Palestinian Red Crescent said it had received requests from the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-30/bombe-rafah-tension-egitto-26579319/">civili di Rafah</a>, but explained that it is "very difficult" to reach them "because of the continuous Israeli bombings".
&nbsp;
In the north of the Strip, three Palestinians, including a child, were killed in a bombing that destroyed their home in the Al-Darraj district of the city of Gaza, according to a hospital source. In the middle, the Deir al-Balah, Bureij and Nousseirat sectors were also targeted by Israeli attacks. The army confirmed the attacks, talking about "mirate" operations to Rafah and in the center of Gaza.&nbsp; In the last 24 hours, according to IDF, 30 terrorist targets have been targeted, including weapons deposits and armed cells. On the diplomatic front, the Qatar, the United States and Egypt mediators jointly asked "Hamas and Israel to finalize the ceasefire agreement based on the principles set out in the href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-31/medio-oriente-biden-hamas-accetti-proposta-israele-tre-fasi-26600207/" After the White House leader explained the terms of the proposal for a three-phase agreement, Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu reiterated his opposition to dealing before destroying Hamas. But the head of government is under pressure: His right-wing ministers, Itamar Ben Gvir and Bezalel Smotrich, threatened to leave the government > if the hostilities were to cease before ending Hamas, while many Israelis continue to go to the square to demand an agreement that guarantees first of all the release of hostages.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The opposition leader Yair Lapid and President Isaac Herzog support the agreement if it plans to release the hostages and protect the security objectives of the state. Hamas considered Biden's proposal positively, but reiterated the request for a ceasefire and a total withdrawal of Israel from Gaza. Today in Cairo there is a meeting between Egypt, the United States and Israel to discuss the Rafah Passage, crucial for the entry of humanitarian aid to Gaza and closed since the Israeli forces took control of the Palestinian side in May. According to the Israeli authorities, 764 Egyptian trucks carrying aid entered Gaza this week through the Kerem Shalom> Pass, but NGOs continue to report that aid does not always reach the population. &nbsp;
