AGI - The President of Chile, Gabriel Boric, has announced that his country will support South Africa before the International Court of Justice in the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-24/corte-international-justice-stop-immediate- Israeli-operation-rafah-26516094/">fall against Israel/a> "I have decided that Chile will become a party in question and will support the case that South Africa has filed against Israel before the International Court of Justice of the Hague, > under the United Nations Convention on Genocide," Boric said in a message to Congress. "There are already more than 35,000 deaths, a catastrophic humanitarian situation and the infrastructure of Gaza practically devastated," said "these acts require a firm response from the international community." The Chilean government had condemned the recent attack by Israeli troops against a Palestinian displaced camp at <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-05-29/medio-orient-francia-consiglio-security-onu-fermi-guerrafah-26563914/">Rafah</a> in the Gaza Strip itself.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
As part of a speech in Parliament to illustrate the budget of government actions and the outline of future policies, the President also denounced the Russian invasion of Ukraine and human rights violations in Nicaragua and Venezuela, before underlining that his country "will never abandon its vocation to dialogue and understanding to ensure a stable and peaceful global order", with a fragmented ovation by the whole House. “Acts in Gaza require an answer from the international community. For this reason, in addition to the humanitarian support we have given to Palestine, to the appeal of our ambassador to Israel and to the presentation, together with Mexico, of a reference to the situation in Palestine to the International Criminal Court, I decided that Chile will join and support the cause brought by South Africa against Israel before the International Court of Justice of the Hague, within the framework of the United Nations Convention on Genocide". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
< blockquote
“We have participated in the development of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. And when these rights have been violated in Chile, we have received the solidarity of all nations and peoples of the world. All this has given rise to a historical commitment that Chile will not abandon in any case"&nbsp;
</blockquote
&nbsp;
In January, Chile, along with Mexico, filed a request to the prosecutor of the International Criminal Court (ICC) to investigate possible war crimes in the context of the conflict between Israel and Hamas. Boric has repeatedly felt that what happens in Gaza "has no justification" or is "justly unacceptable". Chile has recognized the Palestinian state since 2011.>&nbsp; The president also announced that his government will expropriate part of the Colonia Dignidad (260 km south of Santiago), a German enclave founded by a former Nazi nurse and in which Pinochet held political prisoners. Colonia Dignidad was founded in 1961 by former Nazi corporal Paul Schaefer.> The place was presented as an idyllic family city, but in reality Schaefer reigned brutally over hundreds of people, subjecting it to slavery or inflicting sexual abuse on children. After Schaefer's escape in 1997, the Chileans discovered that the German enclave had been a hell for the opponents of Augustus Pinochet's dictatorship: for many of them were tortured or disappeared. He was arrested in 2005 in Argentina, Paul Schaefer died in prison in 2010.&nbsp;&nbsp;
